VALUES
(42, 13, 31, 19, 11, 1, 2, NULL, 'Trust Amid Threats', 'Both passages emphasize the danger posed by wickedness and the call to trust in the Lord despite threats. In Luke, the warning of Herod''s intent to kill Jesus parallels the psalmist''s reflection on fleeing from danger, highlighting a common theme of reliance on God amidst peril.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 31, 40, 14, 1, 1, 'Herod will kill thee', 'Herod''s Threat to Jesus', 'This connection highlights the presence of Herod as a significant figure in both passages. In Luke, the Pharisees warn Jesus about Herod''s intention to kill him, while in Matthew, Herod hears of Jesus'' fame, indicating his awareness of Jesus'' growing influence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 31, 30, 7, 12, 13, 'Get thee out, and depart hence', 'Prophetic Warning and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize a warning to flee due to threats against the prophet''s life. In Luke, Herod''s intent to kill Jesus parallels Amaziah''s command for Amos to leave due to the king''s authority.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 31, 42, 3, 1, 1, 'Herod will kill thee', 'Connection of Herod''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Herod, highlighting his significance in the narrative. In Luke 3:1, Herod is identified as tetrarch, while in Luke 13:31, he is mentioned as a threat to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 32, 58, 2, 10, 10, 'I shall be perfected', 'Perfection through Suffering', 'This connection highlights the theme of perfection achieved through a process. Both passages emphasize the idea of being ''perfected'' in relation to suffering and divine purpose.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 32, 58, 5, 9, 9, 'I shall be perfected', 'Connection of Perfection in Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of perfection in both passages. Luke 13:32 mentions being ''perfected,'' while Hebrews 5:9 states that he ''became perfect,'' emphasizing the completion of Christ''s mission.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 32, 43, 11, 8, 10, 'the third day I shall be perfected', 'Light and Day Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light and the timing of actions. In Luke, Jesus speaks of being active today and tomorrow, while in John, he refers to walking in the day, suggesting a connection between his ministry and the illumination of truth.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 32, 43, 17, 4, 5, 'I shall be perfected', 'Completion of Divine Work', 'This connection highlights the theme of completion in both passages. In Luke, Jesus speaks of being ''perfected'' on the third day, while in John, He declares, ''I have finished the work'' given to Him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 32, 26, 13, 4, 4, 'that fox', 'Fox Imagery in Prophets', 'This connection highlights the use of ''fox'' in both passages, where Luke refers to Herod as a fox, indicating cunningness, while Ezekiel describes false prophets as foxes in the desert, suggesting deceit. Both passages emphasize the negative connotation associated with the term ''fox'' in relation to leadership.', 'keyword', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 32, 42, 9, 7, 9, NULL, 'Connection between Herod and Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the perplexity surrounding Jesus'' identity. In Luke 9:7-9, Herod is confused about who Jesus is, while in Luke 13:32, Jesus asserts his authority and mission, indicating he is actively performing miracles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 32, 42, 23, 8, 11, 'I cast out devils, and I do cures', 'Connection Between Herod and Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the interaction between Jesus and Herod, highlighting Herod''s desire to see miracles and his subsequent mockery of Jesus. The reference to Jesus casting out devils and performing cures in the first passage contrasts with Herod''s dismissive treatment of him in the second.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 33, 42, 9, 53, 53, NULL, 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jerusalem in Jesus'' mission. In Luke 13:33, the necessity of walking towards Jerusalem is highlighted, while Luke 9:53 indicates a determined direction towards the city.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 33, 40, 21, 11, 11, 'for it cannot be that a prophet perish out of Jerusalem', 'Connection of Prophetic Identity', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' identity as a prophet. In Luke, Jesus acknowledges that a prophet cannot perish outside of Jerusalem, while Matthew identifies Him as ''Jesus the prophet.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 33, 40, 20, 18, 18, 'a prophet perish out of Jerusalem', 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jerusalem in the context of prophetic destiny. Luke 13:33 highlights the inevitability of a prophet''s fate in Jerusalem, while Matthew 20:18 specifically mentions the betrayal of the Son of Man there.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 33, 44, 13, 27, 27, 'a prophet perish out of Jerusalem', 'Connection of Jerusalem and Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jerusalem in relation to prophets. Luke highlights that a prophet cannot perish outside of Jerusalem, while Acts notes that the rulers in Jerusalem condemned Jesus despite the prophecies read weekly.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 33, 43, 4, 34, 34, 'for it cannot be that a prophet perish out of Jerusalem', 'Mission and Purpose of Jesus', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' commitment to his mission. In both passages, there is an emphasis on the necessity of fulfilling the work assigned to him, whether it be walking towards Jerusalem or doing the will of the one who sent him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 33, 43, 9, 4, 4, NULL, 'Day and Work Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the urgency of action during the day. Luke highlights the necessity of a prophet''s journey, while John stresses the importance of working while it is day.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 33, 44, 10, 38, 38, 'a prophet perish out of Jerusalem', 'Prophetic Mission of Jesus', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' role as a prophet who must fulfill his mission in Jerusalem, as stated in Luke. Acts emphasizes the anointing of Jesus with power to do good, aligning with his prophetic purpose. Both passages underscore the significance of Jesus'' actions in the context of his prophetic identity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 34, 40, 23, 37, 39, 'O Jerusalem, Jerusalem, which killest the prophets', 'Connection of Lament over Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' lament over Jerusalem''s rejection of prophets. The repeated phrase ''O Jerusalem, Jerusalem'' highlights this sorrowful theme. Additionally, the imagery of gathering children under wings is consistent in both texts.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 34, 5, 32, 11, 12, NULL, 'Imagery of Protective Wings', 'This connection highlights the imagery of protective wings used in both passages. In Luke, Jesus expresses a desire to gather Jerusalem''s children ''under her wings,'' while Deuteronomy describes an eagle that ''spreadeth abroad her wings'' to care for her young.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 34, 23, 30, 15, 15, 'ye would not', 'Rejection of God''s Gathering', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection in both passages, where Jerusalem is depicted as unwilling to be gathered by God, similar to the refusal expressed in Isaiah. Both emphasize a longing for salvation and the people''s unwillingness to accept it.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 34, 44, 7, 52, 52, 'killest the prophets', 'Persecution of Prophets Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the persecution of prophets by Jerusalem. Luke highlights the city''s history of killing prophets, while Acts directly accuses the people of betraying and murdering the Just One, linking their actions to their ancestors'' behavior.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 34, 42, 19, 41, 42, 'how often would I have gathered thy children', 'Connection of Jesus'' Lament', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' sorrow over Jerusalem''s rejection. The imagery of gathering and the lamentation reflect a deep concern for the city''s fate and missed opportunities for peace.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 34, 24, 6, 16, 16, NULL, 'Rejection of Divine Guidance', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection of God''s guidance. Both passages express a longing for the people to turn back to Him, yet they refuse to do so.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 34, 24, 7, 23, 24, 'killest the prophets', 'Rejection of Divine Guidance', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection of God''s messengers. Both passages emphasize the refusal to heed divine guidance, with Luke referencing the killing of prophets and Jeremiah noting the people''s failure to obey God''s voice.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 35, 19, 118, 26, 26, 'Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord', 'Connection of Blessings in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the phrase ''Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord'' in Luke, which directly echoes the sentiment in Psalms. Both passages emphasize the importance of recognizing and blessing those who come from God.', 'quotation', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 35, 41, 11, 9, 10, 'Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord', 'Connection of Messianic Praise', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord,'' linking the recognition of Jesus as the Messiah. Luke''s warning of desolation contrasts with the joyous acclamation in Mark, highlighting the significance of acknowledging Jesus'' arrival.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 35, 40, 21, 9, 9, 'Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord', 'Connection of Messianic Acclamation', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase, ''Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord,'' linking the recognition of Jesus as the Messiah. Luke''s verse anticipates a future acknowledgment of Jesus, while Matthew presents the crowd''s current acclamation during his entry into Jerusalem.', 'quotation', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 35, 43, 12, 13, 13, 'Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord', 'Connection of Messianic Acclamation', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord,'' linking the acknowledgment of Jesus as the Messiah. Luke''s verse anticipates a future recognition of Jesus, while John''s verse depicts the immediate celebration of his arrival.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 35, 28, 3, 4, 5, 'your house is left unto you desolate', 'Desolation and Future Restoration', 'This connection highlights the theme of desolation and the promise of future restoration. Both passages speak to a period of absence and longing for a leader, culminating in a return to God and recognition of His messenger.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
